WEBVTT

00:21.647 --> 00:24.066
<i>(Bill)
The scene is Athens,
400 B. C.</i>

00:24.150 --> 00:27.111
<i>A bunch
of the local brainiacs
have gotten together.</i>

00:27.195 --> 00:30.948
<i>The wine is being passed
and the ideas are flowing
fast and furious.</i>

00:31.032 --> 00:34.285
<i>The debate's in full force.
And Socrates has the floor.</i>

00:34.368 --> 00:38.623
Who enters?
Alcibiades. Drunk.

00:38.706 --> 00:43.252
A beautiful man.
Hopelessly in love
with his mentor, Socrates.

00:43.336 --> 00:46.797
And uniquely,
in all of these dialogs,

00:46.881 --> 00:51.302
Socrates doesn't
get the last word.
Alcibiades does. Why?

00:51.385 --> 00:54.597
<i>(Bill)
Because passion,
Plato seems to be saying,</i>

00:54.680 --> 00:58.559
<i>is essentially
and mercilessly human.</i>

00:58.643 --> 01:01.395
And the best
that we can hope
to do is to quell it

01:01.479 --> 01:03.648
through relentless discipline.

01:03.773 --> 01:08.194
<i>To Socrates,
the healthy life is
comprised of constant focus</i>

01:08.277 --> 01:11.822
<i>by the individual
to excise those forces</i>

01:11.906 --> 01:17.662
that weaken or
confuse his understanding
of the world around him.

01:17.745 --> 01:23.501
He implores us
to devote our lives
to this kind of control.

01:23.584 --> 01:26.462
Meaning , our every
waking moment.

01:26.587 --> 01:32.927
<i>Socrates recognized
what every philosopher
and religion, for that matter</i>

01:33.010 --> 01:37.223
in the history of the world ,
from Plato to Aristotle

01:37.306 --> 01:39.934
from Epicurus to the Stoics

01:40.017 --> 01:42.436
from the Judeo-Christians
to the Buddhists

01:42.520 --> 01:45.398
have all observed

01:45.481 --> 01:53.281
which is that
the balance needed
for a happy life is illusory.

01:53.364 --> 01:57.702
And as soon as
in our gorgeously
flawed human way

01:57.785 --> 02:00.830
we think
that we've attained it

02:00.913 --> 02:05.209
we're pretending divinity
and we're gonna crash.

02:05.293 --> 02:09.005
Like Icarus,
flaming into the sea.

02:09.130 --> 02:13.175
So think about that
this weekend when you think
you're on top of the world

02:13.259 --> 02:16.345
and then you pour
a pitcher of beer
down your throat

02:16.429 --> 02:19.223
and chase
that upper classmen
who's out of your league.

02:22.101 --> 02:26.105
Aristotle is next week.
Don't just look
at it as words.

02:26.230 --> 02:29.734
Imagine the scene.
These were people. They
were alive like you and me.

02:29.817 --> 02:31.819
They thought things.
Breath them into life.

02:31.902 --> 02:33.696
[bells toll]

02:33.779 --> 02:37.033
<i>(Anne)
So, I was thinking
about doing this contrast</i>

02:37.116 --> 02:39.285
<i>between dialog
and chorus in Sophocles.</i>

02:39.368 --> 02:41.746
You should
read Nietzsche's
<i>Birth of Tragedy.</i>

02:41.829 --> 02:43.998
<i>He says that tragedy
emerges from the clash</i>

02:44.081 --> 02:47.543
<i>between Apollo God
of reason and harmony</i>

02:47.626 --> 02:50.463
and Dionysus,
God of intoxication.

02:50.546 --> 02:53.424
And that their struggle
within our human condition

02:53.507 --> 02:55.885
is inevitable
and that that
is what has produced

02:55.968 --> 02:58.596
<i>the most
salient form of art
the world's ever known.</i>

02:58.679 --> 02:59.722
Tragedy?

02:59.805 --> 03:01.098
What, you don't think so?

03:01.182 --> 03:04.310
I like comedies.
You wanna see a movie?

03:04.393 --> 03:07.438
No, Miss Greenstein.
I'm sorry.

03:07.521 --> 03:08.606
Did you get my note?

03:08.689 --> 03:09.732
<i>I did.</i>

03:09.815 --> 03:11.150
